## The supreme rule (unchanged)

**We cut the business before we cut each other.**

Every decision on this timeline, every feature, every launch, is
subordinate to that rule. If the plan starts breaking the family,
we change the plan.

The plan moved from May to December because we were honest about
what May would have cost the family. End-of-year is the version
of this plan that lets us still be married, still be present
parents, and still ship something we're proud of.

The plan is a servant, not a master.

---

## The doctrine moment this plan represents

This rewrite IS the doctrine in action. Six rules:

**Test before trust** — we are giving ourselves time to actually
test, not ship and pray.

**One change at a time** — we are no longer stacking simultaneous
fixes, features, and integrations into the same week.

**Reversible** — every monthly milestone is independently
revertable; nothing on the timeline locks us into outcomes we'd
regret.

**Small radius** — each month touches 1-2 systems, not all of them.

**Preserve optionality** — by waiting, we keep flexibility on
pricing, feature scope, and partnership decisions.

**Diagnose before repair** — we diagnosed that the original plan
was breaking before we tried to repair it. That diagnosis became
this rewrite.

